Sentiment Analysis using tidytext

Sentiment Analysis using TidyVerse

The tidytext package provides access to several sentiment lexicons. Three general-purpose lexicons are:

  • AFINN from Finn rup Nielsen,
  • bing from Bing Liu and collaborators,
  • nrc from Saif Mohammad and Peter Turney.

All three of these lexicons are based on unigrams, i.e., single words. These lexicons contain many English words and the words are assigned scores for positive/negative sentiment, and also possibly emotions like joy, anger, sadness, and so forth. There are also some domain-specific sentiment lexicons available, constructed to be used with text from a specific content area, such as fianance (tm.plugin.webmining) or social medida (vader).

Caveats

  • lexicon-based on unigrams only do not take into account qualifiers before a word, such as in no good or not true
  • the size of text chunk used to add up unigram sentiment scores can effect the analysis. A text the size of many paragraphs can often have positive and negative sentiment averaged out to about zero, while sentence-sized or paragraph-sized text often works better

tidying and text cleaning

Tidy so that the text is in a tidy format with one word per row and also perform text preprocessing

  • remove URLs, numbers, white space
  • stemming or lemmatization. For sentiment, lemmatization may be better as stemming may result in non-words
  • unnest_tokens() for creating a tidy format automatically converts to lowercase, so no need to normalize
  • tidytext also removes punctuation automatically.

Sentiment Analysis.

With data in a tidy format, sentiment analysis can be done as an inner join. First, lets take a look at the 3 sentiment lexicons. Note: need to first download: get_sentiments(nrc)

Word Sentiment Categorization using nrc

get_sentiments("nrc") %>% 
  group_by(sentiment) %>% 
  summarise(n=n())  %>% 
  arrange(-n)
  • The nrc lexicon categorizes words in a binary fashion (yes/no) into categories of positive, negative, anger, anticipation, disgust, fear, joy, sadness, surprise, and trust
  • 10 scale sentiment groupings, including positive and negative

Word Sentiment Categorization using bing

get_sentiments("bing") %>% 
  group_by(sentiment) %>% 
  summarise(n=n())  %>% 
  arrange(-n)
  • The bing lexicon categorizes words in a binary fashion into positive and negative categories
  • 2 scales (positive and negative)

Word Sentiment Categorization using afinn

get_sentiments("afinn") %>% 
  group_by(value) %>% 
  summarise(n=n())  %>% 
  arrange(-n)
  • The AFINN lexicon assigns words with a score that runs between -5 and 5, with negative scores indicating negative sentiment and positive scores indicating positive sentiment.
  • numeric sale from -5 to + 5
